item.title: U.S. Intelligence Agencies Confirm Investigating if Virus Emerged From Lab Accident
item.description: The U.S. intelligence community publicly confirmed it is trying to determine whether the coronavirus may have escaped from a laboratory in Wuhan, the city where the pandemic began.

item.title: U.S. Charges Honduran President's Police Ally in Drug Ring
item.description: Prosecutors and the Drug Enforcement Administration alleged that Juan Carlos Bonilla Valladares used his position to protect politically connected drug traffickers, facilitating multiton shipments of cocaine to the U.S.

item.title: Record Contraction in Eurozone Bodes Ill for Global Economy
item.description: The huge first-quarter decline in Europe portends deep pain and wide economic divergences in 2020.

item.title: U.K.'s Virus Death Toll Draws Scrutiny
item.description: The U.K.’s official death count from the new coronavirus is rapidly rising toward that of Italy, Europe’s worst-hit country so far.

item.title: China Takes Harder Line on Hong Kong Amid Coronavirus Protest Lull
item.description: Tensions are expected to rise in Hong Kong as pro-democracy protesters attempt to return to the streets after a lengthy lull amid the coronavirus pandemic, which authorities have used to push hard against the opposition movement.

item.title: Workers Likely to Fare Better in Nations With Coronavirus Job-Retention Programs
item.description: Workers in Germany and Japan are likely to weather an expected coronavirus-induced global recession better than their U.S. peers, thanks in part to stronger job-retention programs, recent data suggest.
